Three pieces of advice from someone who has run some marathons well, and others abysmally: 



Author::::MarathonPixie
DateTime::::2016-03-06T11:07:57Z
I like to have a bowl of porridge a couple of hours before. Whatever you do, make sure it's tried and tested on your long runs - race day really isn't the time to try something new! 



Author::::jfd1960
DateTime::::2016-03-06T09:46:01Z
I know this is anathema to some marathoners, especially faster runners, but don't be shy of taking walking breaks - better to take regular walking breaks than completely hit the wall at 17 or 18 miles and end up staggering along to the finish. And definitely do this in your long runs, gives your body a break and you'll be a lot less wrecked from an 18-miler the next day or two. And obviously, you need to do those long runs, most important part of your training.



Author::::Shanghaidiver
DateTime::::2016-03-06T08:26:12Z
Point 17..... You don't take Ibuprofen when running (or I Guess other physical exercise). It is paracetamol. Plenty of studies have highlighted the risks of the former. Something to do with the way it does damage to the intestine, kidneys and plays around with your muscles.



